# Problem 2279: echo
# Read any number of characters, output them exactly

# Strategy: Read character, output it, repeat
# When we read 0 (EOF), halt

# Main loop
# Read character into A
A<I

# Check if A == 0 (EOF)
# If A == 0, halt
# We need conditional... Use memory trick:
# Initialize memory location 0 with halt instruction?
# Actually we can do: Z<A (halt if A != 0)
# But we want to halt when A == 0, not when A != 0

# Alternative: Use the fact that [A] is memory address
# Pre-initialize mem[0] with 1 (halt value)
# Then do Z<[A] - if A == 0, Z gets mem[0] = 1, halts
# If A != 0, Z gets mem[A] which is unknown...

# Better: Initialize all memory with 0 except mem[0] = 1
# But initializing all memory is hard

# Actually, we can do: B<A (copy A to B), then Z<B
# But we need to transform: if A == 0, Z = 1; else Z = 0
# We can use a lookup table!

# Initialize lookup table: mem[0] = 1, all other mem[x] = 0
# But we only need mem[0] = 1, memory is already 0-initialized
[0]<1

# Now: Z<[A] - if A == 0, Z = mem[0] = 1, halts
# If A != 0, Z = mem[A] = 0, doesn't halt
Z<[A]

# Output the character (if not EOF)
O<A

# Program loops back to start
# When EOF (A == 0), we halt before outputting 0